# Spec: Sat Jul 11 2026 - sth snapshot test framework

A snapshot test framework. Single self contained program, no dependencies
beyond a shell and sha256sum

The record data is a binary blob of its own so people can not modify it
as they please. Any casual edit breaks the padding markers and the file
is rejected as corrupt.

## File format (record.sth)

All integers are little endian. Every variable length field is a u32
byte length followed by that many bytes (no length prefix means the
format can not be parsed back, since results may contain any bytes
including the padding markers).

Everything after the 8 byte magic is XORed with a keystream so that
catting the file shows no readable content. The keystream is xorshift32
seeded with 0x53544831; each output byte is the low byte of the state
after one round:

    state ^= state << 13
    state ^= state >> 17
    state ^= state << 5
    byte = state & 0xFF

Reset the state to the seed right after the magic on both read and
write. Encode and decode are the same operation. This is obfuscation,
not encryption: it keeps the blob opaque to cat/strings and casual
editing, nothing more.

    header:  magic "STHREC01" (8 bytes) | u32 entry-count
    entry:   u8  state
             [file-name] || [cmd] | [sha256-hash] | [expected-return-status] | [result] ||

    |  -> 4 byte padding, bytes 00 FF 00 FF
    || -> 8 byte padding, bytes 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF

The padding is an integrity marker: on read, every pad must match
exactly after decoding or the file is reported corrupt. All tests are
stored in this one file.

*state*: u8. 0 = SET (registered via -set, not yet recorded),
 1 = RECORDED (has a valid hash, status and result snapshot).

*file-name*: length prefixed char[] storing the path of the file the
 test checks.

*cmd*: length prefixed char[] storing the build command, e.g.
 "gcc -Isrc/ -Wall -Wpedantic $file -o $file.exe". Every occurrence of
 $file is expanded to file-name at run time, not at set time. The cmd
 must produce <file-name>.exe. It is a build step only; the framework
 runs the exe itself.

*sha256-hash*: 65 bytes fixed (64 hex chars + nul), the sha256 of
 file-name taken at record time. On verify, a hash mismatch means the
 source file was modified or is missing, which is a failure telling the
 user to rerecord. Zeroed while state is SET.

*expected-return-status*: i32 storing the exit status of the exe from
 the initial record, so that when the user reruns the test it checks if
 the status is still the expected one.

*result*: length prefixed char[] storing the combined stdout+stderr of
 the exe from the initial record. On verify the fresh output is compared
 byte for byte against this; any mismatch is reported as a per line diff
 (- expected / + got, with line numbers).

## Execution model

record (per entry):
  1. hash file-name, store it
  2. run cmd with $file expanded; nonzero build status = record failure,
     show the build output
  3. run <file-name>.exe, capture stdout+stderr and exit status as the
     snapshot
  4. delete the exe
  5. mark entry RECORDED

verify (per recorded entry):
  1. hash file-name, compare against stored hash; mismatch = FAIL
  2. build; build failure = FAIL, show build output
  3. run the exe, capture output and status
  4. delete the exe
  5. compare status and output against the snapshot; report [ OK ] or
     [FAIL] with the status mismatch and/or line diff
  6. after all entries print "N ran, M failed", exit 0 if none failed,
     else 1

The exe runs from the framework's working directory, so relative paths
inside the tested program (data files it opens etc.) resolve relative
to where the framework is invoked. Run record and verify from the same
directory.

## Command line flags

./program -set -f file_name -cmd 'gcc -I../src/ $file -o $file.exe'
    Register file_name with a build cmd, or replace the cmd of an
    existing entry. Quote the cmd in single quotes so the shell does
    not expand $file before the program sees it.

./program -file
    Instead of hard coding the path for record.sth to be only in current.
    working directory we can also make use of providing the path for the
    record.sth making moved file still work.

./program -dir
    Change the current working directory into the specified directory.
    Use that dir as basedir for finding record.sth and running all the
    test cases that are required.

./program -record
    Find all set-but-unrecorded entries in record.sth and record them.

./program
    Read record.sth, run every recorded test and report any mismatch.

./program -rerecord -f file_name <optional cmd>
    Rerecord one test, refreshing hash, status and result. If cmd is
    not provided it uses the cmd from the -set flag, otherwise the new
    cmd replaces it.

./program -rerecord -all
    Rerecord all pre-existing test cases, setting new expected results
    and hashes while keeping the file-names and cmds.

./program -help
    Print all commands with descriptions to stdout, exit 0.

Bad or missing arguments print a short usage to stderr and exit 1.c
